üéõÔ∏è workctl Shortcut Design Principles

Before the map, these are the rules we follow (important):

Single-letter flags are for frequent actions

Letters should be mnemonic

No collisions

Shortcuts never replace canonical commands

Flags = actions, Commands = nouns

This keeps the CLI intuitive under stress.

üß≠ Core Shortcut Map (Recommended)
üî• Daily-use shortcuts (muscle memory)
Shortcut	Command	Meaning	Why this letter
-p	pomodoro	Focus session	Pomodoro
-t	priority	Top priority tasks	Top tasks
-f	follow-ups (future)	What am I waiting on	Follow-up
-n	next (future)	What should I do next	Next action

These should become reflexes.

üß† Thinking & reflection shortcuts
Shortcut	Command	Meaning
-d	record-decision	Log a decision
-m	generate-markdown	Generate report / summary

Mnemonic:

Decide

Markdown / Memo

ü§ñ Automation & agents
Shortcut	Command	Meaning
-a	create-tasks	Run email ‚Üí task agent
-r	run-agents (future)	Run all background agents

Use these sparingly ‚Äî agents shouldn‚Äôt need frequent manual triggers.

üõ†Ô∏è Meta / system shortcuts
Shortcut	Command	Meaning
-s	status (future)	System health
-h	help	Help (standard)
-v	version (future)	Version info
‚úÖ Canonical Commands (Never removed)

Shortcuts are aliases, not replacements.

These should always work:

workctl pomodoro
workctl priority
workctl create-tasks
workctl record-decision

üß© Visual Summary (Mental Model)
Focus        ‚Üí -p
Decide       ‚Üí -d
Act next     ‚Üí -n
Check tasks  ‚Üí -t
Follow up   ‚Üí -f
Automate    ‚Üí -a
Reflect     ‚Üí -m


This maps nicely to how a CTO‚Äôs day flows.

üß± Implementation Pattern (for workctl)

This is how your shortcuts should resolve internally:

SHORTCUTS = {
    "-p": "pomodoro",
    "-t": "priority",
    "-d": "record-decision",
    "-m": "generate-markdown",
    "-a": "create-tasks",
}


All shortcuts ‚Üí canonical commands ‚Üí handlers in COMMAND_ROUTES.

No duplication. No branching logic everywhere.

üö´ Shortcuts to avoid (important)
Shortcut	Why avoid
-c	Ambiguous (create / close / config)
-l	Conflicts with common shell patterns
-x	Too generic
-1, -2	Non-mnemonic
üß† Why this works long-term

You‚Äôll remember it under pressure

New commands slot in naturally

Other people can learn it in 2 minutes

It mirrors tools like git, kubectl, terraform

This is tool ergonomics, not aesthetics.

