workctl Shortcut Map

This document defines the official shortcut map for the workctl command-line tool.

Shortcuts are designed for high-frequency actions, while canonical commands remain the primary interface.

Design Principles

Shortcuts are mnemonic (easy to remember)

Shortcuts are optional ‚Äî canonical commands always work

One shortcut = one action

No collisions

Flags express actions, commands express nouns

Core Daily Shortcuts

These are intended to become muscle memory.

Shortcut	Canonical Command	Description
-p	pomodoro	Start a 25-minute Pomodoro focus session
-t	priority	Show top priority tasks
-f	follow-ups (planned)	Show pending follow-ups
-n	next (planned)	Show next best action
Thinking & Reflection

Used for deliberate thinking, review, and documentation.

Shortcut	Canonical Command	Description
-d	record-decision	Record a decision
-m	generate-markdown	Generate Markdown report from work logs
Automation & Agents

Used to manually trigger background automation.

Shortcut	Canonical Command	Description
-a	create-tasks	Run email ‚Üí task creation agent
-r	run-agents (planned)	Run all background agents
System & Meta
Shortcut	Canonical Command	Description
-s	status (planned)	Show system health
-h	help	Show help
-v	version (planned)	Show version information
Canonical Commands (Always Supported)

Shortcuts are aliases only.
The following commands must always work:

workctl pomodoro
workctl priority
workctl create-tasks
workctl record-decision
workctl generate-markdown

Mental Model
-p  Focus (Pomodoro)
-t  Top tasks
-d  Decide
-m  Reflect
-a  Automate

Implementation Notes

Shortcuts are resolved in workctl

Canonical commands are defined in src/cli/commands.py

Business logic must not depend on shortcuts

Extending the Shortcut Map

When adding new shortcuts:

Ensure the action is high-frequency

Choose a mnemonic letter

Avoid collisions

Update this document

Status

This document represents the authoritative shortcut specification for workctl.

